[B] Bangladesh
Date: Fri 18 Dec 2020 03:34 AM BdST
Source: The Daily Star [edited]
https://www.thedailystar.net/backpage/news/covid-positivity-rate-dips-8-month-low-2013181


The rate of daily positive coronavirus cases dropped yesterday [17 Dec 2020] to 8.6 percent, the lowest it has been in more than 8 months, while the recovery rate continued to increase.

In 24 hours ending at 8:00 am yesterday [17 Dec 2020], a total of 13 191 tests were performed in 140 COVID-19 testing centres across the country and 1134 tested positive for the virus. 36 people died with the highly transmissible virus over the same period

The previous lowest daily positivity rate was on [10 Apr 2020], when 7.93 percent of 1184 samples tested positive for COVID-19.

The percentage of positive cases is a critical measure because it gives an indication of how widespread the infection is in the area where testing is occurring and whether levels of testing are keeping up with levels of disease transmission, according to Johns Hopkins University.

A high percentage of positive cases means that more testing should probably be done, and it suggests that it is not a good time to relax restrictions aimed at reducing coronavirus transmission.

As a rule of thumb, the positivity rate is thought to be "too high" if it is more than 5 percent.

In May [2020], the World Health Organization recommended that the positivity rate should be below 5 percent for at least 2 weeks before governments considered reopening.

"Although the positivity rate was decreasing in the last several days, it may rise at any time. In fact, the transmission will show both rising and decreasing trends in the coming days, as we observed during higher [rates of] transmission earlier (May-July 2020)," Mushtuq Hussain, consultant of the Institute of Epidemiology, Disease Control and Research (IEDCR) told The Daily Star yesterday [17 Dec 2020].

Since the 1st 3 confirmed cases were reported on [8 Mar 2020] in the country, the transmission of COVID-19 was highest between June and July [2020].

The highest daily positivity rate of 31.91 was recorded on [3 Aug 2020]. It remained stagnant at around 12 percent throughout September and October [2020]. From November 2020, however, it started rising again.

Yesterday's [17 Dec 2020] infections took the total number of cases in the country to 496 975.

In the same 24 hours, 2239 patients recovered from their illnesses, raising the total number of recoveries to 431 590. This is 86.84 percent of all confirmed cases, up from 86.59 the previous day.

The number of deaths from COVID-19 was 36 over the 24-hour period, which is higher than the previous day's deaths, at 27.

The total number of COVID-19 deaths in the country now stands at 7192, which is 1.44 percent of all confirmed cases.

Among the 36 deceased, 27 were male. One of them was aged between 31 and 40 years, 2 between 41 and 50, 4 between 51 and 60, and 29 were above 60 years, according to the release.

[Byline: Moudud Ahmmed Sujan]

